## C++ modernization preferences

The toolchain ships modern C++ — agents should write code that uses it,
not 2003 idioms grand-fathered through legacy projects.

- Prefer C++23 / 20 idioms when they improve clarity:
  `std::ranges`, `std::format`, `std::print`, `std::expected`,
  `std::optional`, `std::span`, `std::string_view`.
- RAII over manual resource management. **No raw `new` / `delete`** in
  user code (smart pointers, containers, scoped objects only).
- **Avoid C-style casts** (use `static_cast` / `reinterpret_cast` /
  `dynamic_cast` / `const_cast` so the intent is explicit).
- Use `std::expected<T, E>` for fallible operations that have meaningful
  errors (`std::optional<T>` if "absence" is the only failure mode).
- Pass non-owning views by `std::span` / `std::string_view`; pass owning
  values by value or const-ref per the usual rules.
- Prefer `std::print` / `std::format` over `printf` / iostream chains.
